ted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith the growth of knowledge-based economies, cities across the globe must compete to attract and retain the most talented workers. Seeking Talent for Creative Cities offers a comprehensive and insightful analysis of the diverse, dynamic factors that affect cities’ ability to achieve this goal.Based on a comparative national study of 16 Canadian cities, this volume systematically evaluates the concerns facing workers operating in a range of creative endeavours. It draws on interviews, surveys, and census data collected over a six-year research program conducted by experts in business, public policy, urban studies, and communications studies to identify the characteristics and features of particular city-regions that influence these workers’ mobility and satisfaction. Seeking Talent for Creative Cities represents a rigorously empirical test of popular wisdom on the true relationship between urban development and economic competitiveness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aCities and townszCanadaxGrowthvCase studies. 0aCultural industrieszCanadavCase studies. 0aDiffusion of innovationszCanadavCase studies. 0aSociology, UrbanzCanadavCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh1 aGrant, Jill, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Pilot 2014-2015z978311060681240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266793840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442667938423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442667938.jpg  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Pilot 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL 